ester, Lancashire, England","England":"England","Lathom St James, Lancashire, England":"Lathom St James, Lancashire, England","London, England":"London, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Reeves","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Reeve  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","English: from Middle English <i>reve</i> + genitival <i>-s</i>, for the son, daughter, wife, or servant of a reeve or of someone surnamed   Reeve  .","English: from Middle English <i>atte Reves</i>, a topographic and occupational name for someone who lived and probably worked ‘at the reeve's (house)’."],"variants":[{"name":"Reves","meanings":["Americanized form of Hungarian <b>Révész</b>, an occupational name for a ferryman, <i>révész</i>.","English: variant of   Reeves  .","English: variant of   Revis  ."]},{"name":"Rieves","meanings":["Perhaps an altered form of English   Reeves  , Hungarian <b>Révész</b> (see   Reves  ), or avariant of German   Riewe  ."]},{"name":"Reeve","meanings":["English (East Anglia): occupational name from Middle English <i>reve</i>, <i>refe</i> ‘reeve’ (Old English <i>gerēfa</i>). In medieval England a reeve was an official responsible for the administration of a manor, including organizing work done by the peasants on the land for their lord, collecting rents, selling produce, and so on.","Irish: variant of   Reeves   5."]},{"name":"Reavis","meanings":["English: variant of   Reeves  ."]},{"name":"Reaves","meanings":["English: variant of   Reeves  ."]},{"name":"Revis","meanings":["English:","habitational name for someone from Rievaulx (North Yorkshire), traditionally pronounced <i>Rivers</i>. The placename derives from the river name <i>Rye</i> (of uncertain etymology) + Old French <i>vals</i> ‘vale, wide valley’.","variant of   Reeves  ."]}]},{"name":"Samantha","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of problematic and much debated origin. It arose in the United States at the end of the 18th century, possibly as a combination of <i>Sam</i> (from   Samuel  ) + a newly coined feminine suffix <i>-antha</i> (perhaps suggested by   Anthea  )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Maryanne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Extended spelling of   Marian  , reinforcing the association of the second element with   Ann(e) .  It also represents a French assimilated form of   Mariamne .  <i>Marianne</i> is the name used for the symbolic figure of the French Republic."],"variants":[{"name":"Mariana","meanings":["Extended spelling of   Marian  , reinforcing the association of the second element with   Ann(e) .  It also represents a French assimilated form of   Mariamne .  <i>Marianne</i> is the name used for the symbolic figure of the French Republic."]},{"name":"Marieanne","meanings":["Extended spelling of   Marian  , reinforcing the association of the second element with   Ann(e) .  It also represents a French assimilated form of   Mariamne .  <i>Marianne</i> is the name used for the symbolic figure of the French Republic."]},{"name":"Mariann","meanings":["Extended spelling of   Marian  , reinforcing the association of the second element with   Ann(e) .  It also represents a French assimilated form of   Mariamne .  <i>Marianne</i> is the name used for the symbolic figure of the French Republic."]},{"name":"Marianna","meanings":["Extended spelling of   Marian  , reinforcing the association of the second element with   Ann(e) .  It also represents a French assimilated form of   Mariamne .  <i>Marianne</i> is the name used for the symbolic figure of the French Republic."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":4,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100